column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: DRIVER CAME INTO SOUTH BEND TERMINAL ENROUTE FROM CHGO TO AKRON & REPORTED SOMETHING WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  WE CHECKED THE UNIT TO SEE IF WE COULD ASCERTAIN WHAT WAS LEAKING, DECIDED IT WAS THE NOVAMAX SHIPMENT & CALLED CHEMTREC.  THEY GAVE ME THE PHONE # OF THE CONTACT @ NOVAMAX, I CALLED HIM & DESCRIBED THE INCIDENT.  HE SAID IT COULD BE FLUSHED WITH WATER & LET RUN INTO OUR STORM BASIN.  I CALLED NORTHERN INDIANA MECHANICAL FOR THE CLEANUP.  IN THE MEANTIME, NOVAMAX CALLED BACK & SAID HE FORGOT TO TELL ME THE PRODUCT COULD BE POTENTIALLY HAZARDOUS IF IT CAME INTO CONTACT WITH CARDBOARD OR WOOD.  I TOLD HIM THE TRAILER WAS FULL OF CARDBOARD BOXES & WOODEN SKIDS.  HE SAID TO LET THE CLEAN-UP COMPANY DECIDE IF THE LOCAL HAZMAT TEAM SHOULD BE CALLED.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, THE SITUATION WAS ASSESSED & THEY DETERMINED WE NEEDED TO CALL THE SOUTH BEND HAZMAT TEAM.  THEY TOOK OVER @ APPROX 09:00 & THE SOLUTION WAS DILLUTED THEN TO L/T 10PPM @ WHICH TIME IT WAS DETERMINED BY BJIM MINSEY WHO IS A CHEMIST @ THE SOUTH BEND WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT THAT THE MAT'L COULD BE DRAINED INTO OUR CATCH BASIN.  IT WAS, & EVERYTHING WAS CLEAR @ APPROXIMATELY 16:00.

THE ROLL-OFF BOX AND ITS CONTENTS WERE TRANSPORTED TO ITS INTENDED DESTINATION, SUBURBAN SOUTH R&DF, 3415 HOPEWELL TOWNSHIP ROAD 477, OHIO 43739 FOR DISPOSAL. DURING SWITCHING OPERATION THE SWITCH CREW DISCOVERED PLCX 129103, LEAKING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY COVER.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CP RAIL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR WAS CALLED TO INSPECT THE CAR.  HE FOUND THAT 6 OF THE 8 BOLTS THAT SECURE THE MANWAY WERE LOOSE TO THE POINT THEY COULD BE TIGHTENED BY HAND.  ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO BILLED DESTINATION.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN UP NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

TANK CAR REPORTED TO HAVE SLOSHED PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT RAIL YARD IN SAGANAW, MI.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED.  CSXT ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER THROUGH THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER ON THE SHIPPING PAPER BUT WAS UNABLE TO REACH ANYONE WHO COULD PROVIDE ANY ASSISTANCE.  ON 10/14, CSXT CALLED THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY AND ADVISED THEM OF THE PROBLEM.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED WITH PERSONNEL FROM THEIR ALSENA, MI PLANT.  SHIPPER FOUND CAR HAD A DETERIORATED MANWAY COVER GASKET.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED BY THE SHIPPER.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT RECEIVER TO FIND THAT 6 OF THE TOTE TANKS INSIDE THE TRAILER HAD LEAKED INTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TANKS HAD VALVES AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKS AND HAD SEEPED SOME PRODUCT INTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER BECAUSE WHEN THE VALVES WERE CLOSED, THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE DRAIN TUBE WAS SUPPOSED TO HAVE BEEN CAPPED OFF WITH RUBBER CORKS TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE VALVES.  ALL WASTE WAS PICKED UP USING ABSORBENT AND WAS DISPOSED OF BY THE RECEIVER.

PRODUCT DELIVERY HOSE BURST DURING FIRST MOMENTS OF DELIVERY.  HOSE WAS EXAMINED AND FOUND TO BE IN EXCELLENT CONDITION AND HAD BEEN PRESSURE TESTED 3 MONTHS PRIOR TO THIS DELIVERY.  POSSIBLE CONTRIBUTING FACTOR COULD HAVE BEEN THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVING LINE WAS BLOCKED OR RESTRICTED.
THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY.  TWO OF SEVEN BOTTLES HAD BEEN DAMAGED.  THE CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURE.

ONE OF FOUR GALLONS CONTAINERS OF SHIPMENTS (IN) WAS FOUND WITH LID PARTIALLY OPENED.  THIS CAUSED LEAKAGE.  NO DIVIDERS WERE USED IN THE PACKAGE.  DAMAGED PARTIES DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING PROCEDURE-CUSTOMER SERVICE FOLLOW UP WITH SHIPPER.
THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS NOTICED AND A SUPERVISOR WAS CONSULTED IMMEDIATELY.  THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE MALLINCKRODT PROCEDURE AND THE PACKAGE WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.
THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING ON BOXLINE 5.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING PROPER HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING ON THE PD-12.  THE CONTENTS WERE SHIPPED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE DUE TO VERY SMALL AMOUNT LEAKING OUT.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

column168: AT 19:10 HOURS, 10-5-93, CREW SWITCHING IN MOSSVILLE YARD REPORTED STRONG ODOR COMING FROM CAR.  CAR WAS INSPECTED BY KCS PERSONNEL LEAK.  ENTIRE AREA AROUND MOSSVILLE HAD A STRONG ODOR IN THE AIR AS A RESULT OF CONOCO BURNING OFF HYDROGEN SULFIDE THAT HAD ACCUMULATED WHEN THEIR GASOLINE PROCESSING UNIT SCRUBBERS BECOME DIRTY.  HOWEVER, A STRONG ODOR OF MERCAPTAN WAS NOTICED AROUND CAR.  AT 20:10, SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND GIVEN INFORMATION FROM KCS PERSONNEL EXAMINATION OF CAR.  AT 23:05, SHIPPER ARRIVED AND IMMEDIATELY INSPECTED CAR.  AFTER THEIR INSPECTION, THEY DETERMINED THAT DUE TO STRONG ODOR THERE WAS A PROBLEM WITH THE CAR BUT THEY COULD NO FIND A LEAK.  SHIPPER INDICATED ODOR FROM CAR PRESENTED NO HEALTH PROBLEM  AND CAR WAS SAFE ENOUGH TO RETURN TO SHIPPER 3:15 HOUR, 10-7-93.  A PRESSURE TEST WAS MADE ON THE CAR AND FOUND A SMALL MANWAY COVER GASKET LEAK.  LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS SO MINUTE THAT IT IS NOT DETECTABLE OR MEASURABLE.  CAR WAS BUILT IN MARCH 1993 AND THEREFORE A NEW CAR  .SHIPPER INDICATES THEY ARE GOING TO CHECK THE REST OF THEIR NEW FLEET OF CARS TO DETERMINE IF THERE IS A PROBLEM AND ESTABLISH MEASURE TO MONITOR CARS AFTER BEING LOADED FOR 2 DAYS BEFORE RELEASING THEM FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: DISCHARGE VALVE ON TOP OF MC312 TANKER DISCOVERED TO BE 2/3 OPEN BY DRIVER WHEN LEAK FROM DISCHARGE PIPE WAS NOTICED AFTER STOP SIGN/SPEED BUMP AT MOUNT VERNON, IOWA.  DUST CAP FOR DISCHARGE PIPE WAS PRESENT BUT HANGING ON CHAIN, NOT IN PLACE CLOSING PIPE.  WHEN DRIVER THEN CLOSED VALVE FULLY AND DISCHARGE PIPE CAP REPLACED, NO FURTHER LEAK RESULTED.  VERTEX AIR TESTED VALVE AND DISCOVERED NO FAULT.  CAP WAS INTACT AND ABLE TO BE TIGHTLY SECURED AFTER THE INCIDENT.  WE BELIEVE THAT IRREGULARITIES ON ROAD CAUSED PRODUCT TO SLOSH UP AND LEAK THRU THE PARTLY OPENED VALVE.  WE BELIEVE THE CAP MUST NOT HAVE BEEN COMPLETELY SECURED EITHER DUE TO TAMPERING ENROUTE OR IMCOMPLETE CLOSURE PRIOR TO DEPARTURE.  LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM SANDED THE SPILL AREA, AND REMOVED WASTE SAN FROM SCENE.  VERTEX IS INVESTIGATING A: LOCK/SECURITY METHOD FOR PRODUCT/AIR VALVES; B: LOCK/SECURITY METHOD FOR DISCHARGE CAPS, THESE WILL BE INSTALLED IMPLEMENTED.  PROBLEM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DRIVER ERROR OR POSSIBLY VANDALISM.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE CORGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE MADE A U-TURN AT A DRIVEWAY. THE TURN WAS QUITE SHARP AND AS HE CAME AROUND, THE TRACTOR HIT A DIP IN THE DRIVEWAY CAUSING THE MUD FLAP BRACKET OF THE TRACTOR TO HIT AND PUNCTURE THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET THE INTERNAL PART OF THE VALVE TO RE-SEAT BUT NOT AFTER 315 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED.  CLEAN-UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY REMOVING THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND REPLACING IT WITH GOOD SOIL AND GRAVEL AS APPLICABLE.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WILL BE LAND FARMED UNTIL DRY, THEN DISPOSED OF AS REQUIRED BY COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH.

column168: THE CARGO TANK VEHICLE WAS NORTH BOUND ON I-15.  THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND DROVE OFF THE ROAD INTO THE MEDIAN OF THE INTERSTATE. THE TRACTOR AND CARGO TANK ROLLED 3/4/ OF A TURN AND CAME TO REST ON THEIR RIGHT SIDE - IN THE MEDIAN OF THE INTERSTATE.  THE PROVO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE UTAH HIGHWAY PATROL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE ABOVE ENTITIIES CLOSED THE INTERSTATE UNTIL RECOVERY OF THE UNITS WAS COMPLETE - APPR. 12HOUR.  THERE WAS XXX NO LEAKAGE FROM THE CARGO TANK, NOR WAS THERE ANY EMINENT HAZARD OF A LEAK IN EVIDENCE.  THE REASON FOR THIS REPORT IS THE FACT THAT THE INTERSTATE 15 WAS CLOSED TO TRAFFIC FOR A PERIOD OF 12 HOURS.

THE ORIOLE UNIT WAS NORTHBOUND ON PA RTE 100 TRANSPORTING 44,840 POUNDS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE 50% SOLUTION.  THE DRIVER STOPPED FOR A TRAFFIC SIGNAL AT THE INTERSECTION OF PA RTE 100 AND RTE 113.  WHEN UNIT STARTED UP A SMALL QUANTITY OF MATERIAL CAME OUT OF THE TOP REAR FUSIBLE CAP/CLEAN OUT.  IT SPLASH IN THE TRACTORS REAR VIEW MIRROR AND STOPPED THE UNIT ON THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER.  THE DRIVER MADE SURE THAT THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL CHANCE OF SPILLAGE.  HE NOTIFIED THE TERMINAL MANAGER AND THE LOCAL POLICE WHO DETOURED NORTHBOUND TRAFFIC AROUND THE INTERSECTION.  UPON CONFERRING WITH THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL, A DECISION WAS MADE TO DILUTE THE ALREADY DRYING SPILL WITH WATER AND NEUTRALIZE IT WITH A SMALL QUANTITY OF CITRIC ACID.  THE CITRIC ACID WAS SENT TO THE SITE FORM THE DELAWARE CITY, DE TERMINAL.  ALL MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED TO THE PROPER PH AND NO WASTE WAS GENERATED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE STAINLESS STEEL FUSIBLE CAP AT THE REAR CLEAN OUT FAILED,  ALLOWING MATERIAL TO BE RELEASED FORM THE TRAILER.  THE SOLDER SECURING THE CENTER TO COME LOOSE.  IT APPEARS THAT THE CAP BEGAN FAILING SOUTH OF THE INTERSECTION.  THIS WAS THE FIRST FUSIBLE CAP FAILURE ORIOLE HAD EVER EXPERIENCED.  THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS HAVE BEEN TAKEN.   1)  ALL FUSIBLE CAPS HAVE BEEN INSPECTED.  2)  ALL FUSIBLE CAPS WILL BE REPLACED BY OCTOBER 30, 1993.  SO WE WILL KNOW THE AGE OF ALL IN-SERVICE CAPS.  3)  THE INSTALLATION, WHEN POSSIBLE, OF FUSIBLE CAPS ON NIPPLES NOT INTENDED FOR THE USE OF CLEANING OR LOADING. 4)  THE RETRAINING OF ALL ORIOLE MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL IN THE PROPER INSPECTION, INSTALLATION, AND USE OF FUSIBLE CAPS AND GASKETS.  5)  THE CONTINUATION OF PURCHASING ONLY GIRARD EQUIPMENT CO. DESIGN AND MANUFACTURED FUSIBLE CAPS.  THIS CAP WAS A GIRARD CAP.  6)  FOR A PERIOD OF AT LEAST ONE YEAR, IN ORDER TO INCREASE OUR KNOWLEDGE OF THE PERFORMANCE AND USE OF GIRARD CAPS, THE ORIOLE MAINTENANCE MANAGER WILL INSPECT AND REPLACE, IF NECESSARY, EVERY FUSIBLE CAP.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM VITRAMON, INC. LOCATED AT 3435 CHIP DRIVE IN ROANOKE, VA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. THE CONTAINERS FROM VITRAMON, INC. WERE BEING TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER VAN TRAILER. DURING THIS OPERATION, THE FORK-LIFT BEING USED TO FACILITATE THE TRANSFER OF THE CONTAINERS PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS CAUSING THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF DICHLOROMETHANE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER USED TO TRANSPORT THE MATERIAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED ON THE SAFE OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR THE USE OF FORK-LIFTS WHEN LOADING OR OFF LOADING VAN TRAILERS.

CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE MASSACHUSETTS PREPARED A TANK LOAD OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. (CONTAINING HEXANE & TOLUENE) FOR SHIPMENT TO SYSTECH CORP. LOCATED ON COUNTRY ROAD 176 IN PAULDING, OH. UPON COMPLETION OF THE LOADING PROCEDURES, THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO MOVE THE CARGO TANK TO THE ON-SITE SCALE TO OBTAIN A WEIGHT READING. PRIOR TO MOVING THE VEHICLE, THE DRIVER VISUALLY INSPECTED THE DOME HATCH BUT DID NOT PHYSICALLY CHECK TO MAKE SURE THAT ALL OF THE BOLTS ON THE HATCH WERE THE SECURED. WHEN THE DRIVER BACKED OFF THE SCALE, THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK SURGED TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WITH SPEEDI DRY WHICH WAS, IN TURN, DISPOSED OF THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. PRIOR TO MOVING THE VEHICLE, ALL CLOSURES WERE INSPECTED AND PROPERLY SEALED. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THE LOADING AND MOVING OF CARGO TANKS HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER PRE-TRIP PROCEDURES AND INSPECTIONS THAT MUST BE TAKEN PRIOR TO MOVING ANY VEHICLE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR TRACTOR AND TRAILER WENT INTO A DITCH ROLLED ON ITS SIDE WITH A LOAD OF METHONAL, APPARENTLY THE DRIVER FELL ASLEEP AT THE WHEEL. APPROXIMATELY 343 GALLONS SEEPED FROM THE DOMES OF THE TRAILER BEFORE WE WERE ABLE TO TRANSFER THE LOAD TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  THE POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY TESTED THE SITE AND COULD NOT FIND ANY CONTAMINATION DUE TO THE SPILL OF METHONAL.  THE WIND WAS STRONG CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO EVAPORATE VERY FAST.  THE SITE HAS BEEN CLEANED AND CHECKED OUT BY THE MINNESOTA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND WVERYTHING IS BACK TO NORMAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 13, 1993, SIMONS PETROLEUM'S DRIVER CECIL PISTOLE WAS HAULING APPROXIMATELY 7,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO AN OFF-ROAD OIL AND GAS DRILLING RIG LOCATION ONE MILE WEST OF VERDEN, OKLAHOMA, JUST OFF OF HIGHWAY 62.  TO ENTER ON TO THE ROAD FROM THE HIGHWAY TO THE RIG REQUIRED THE DRIVER TO MAKE A DIFFICULT REGRESSIVE 90 DEGREE TURN.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO NEGOTIATE THE TURN, WHICH PLACED THE REAR WHEELS AT OR OVER THE EDGE OF THE RIG ROAD, CAUSING THE TRAILER TO ROLL OVER ON ITS SIDE AND PULLING THE TRACTOR OVER ON ITS SIDE.  PICTURE ATTACHED.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF DIESEL, APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS, AFFECT ANY WATERS OF THE UNITED STATES.  EVERYTHING WAS CLEANED UP BY EVENING IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE OKLAHOMA CORPORATION COMMISSION AND UNDER THE DIRECTION OF WHITETAIL SERVICES, INC., AN ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY WITH AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT. THE DRIVER WAS UNINJURED AND WAS NOT ASKED TO TAKE A DRUG TEST.  UPON REVIEW, HIS EMPLOYMENT WAS TERMINATED.

TOW MOTOR OPERATOR WAS IN THE PROCESS OF PICKING UP A PALLET OF TOP LOADED FREIGHT.  HAZARDOUS DRUMS WERE COVERED WITH A SHEET OF PARTICLE BOARD. WHEN PALLET BEGAN SLIPPING ON TOW MOTOR FORKS, THE OPERATOR LOWERED PALLET TO GET MORE OF THE FORKS BACK UNDER THE PALLET.  THE OPERATOR LET THE FORKS REST ON THE PARTICLE BOARD TO LET THEM SLIDE BACK UNDER THE PALLET. INSTEAD OF LETTING THE FORKS SLIDE, THE PARTICLE BOARD GAVE WAY AS THE TOW MOTOR STARTED  MOVING FORWARD.  THE LEFT FORK SLID BENEATH THE BOARD AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM ABOUT 4-6 INCHES BELOW THE CHIME.  THE OPERATOR STOPPED AND BACKED THE FORKLIFT UP.  THE ONLY MATERIAL SPILLED WAS FROM THE INITIAL SLOSH AS THE FORK PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE PUNCTURE WAS ABOVE THE LIQUID LINE.  ACTION TAKEN:  CALLED HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ-MAT TEAM. TEAM RESPONDED AND PATCHED DRUM.

column168: PACKAGE WAS PART OF INBOUND PACKAGE LOAD INTO MORGANTOWN, WEST VA. THE PACKAGES WERE BEING UNLOADED WHEN A STRONG ODOR WAS DISCOVERED COMING OUT OF THE VEHICLE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE LOCAL AREA RESPONDED. THE FIRE CAPTAIN IDENTIFIED THE CONTAINER OF METHYL CYANIDE AS BEING THE CULPRIT PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 3 VITALS AT 940ML EACH. ONE OF THE VIALS HAS A LOOSE TOP WHICH APPARENTLY WAS THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR. NO SEALS OR TAPE WERE BROKEN NOR WAS THERE ANY SIGN OF EXTERNAL DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A LEAKING LIQUID BUT THE ODOR WAS APPARENT. THE FAA CASFU AT PITTSBURG WAS  NOTIFIED OF THE EVACUATION.

TRUCK WAS TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED DUE TO TANK UNABLE TO HOLD ENTIRE DELIVERY.  CHEMICALS OVERFLOWED INTO CONTAINMENT AREA.  CONSIGNEE HADNLED SPILL CLEAN-UP.

PACKAGES CAME IN CORRODED WITH LIDS COMING OFF.  DRUM WITH MOST CORROSION TAPED AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  OTHER DRUMS LIDS WERE ABLE TO BE RESEALED AND DELIVERED CLEAR.  DRIVER HAD BEEN WARNED ABOUT PICKING UP IMPROPERLY PACKAGED FREIGHT, AS WELL AS RESPONSIBLE SUPERVISORS.

column42: CALCIUM HYPOCHLORITE, HYDRATED OR CALCIUM HYPOCHLORITE, HYDRATED MIXTURES, WITH NOT LESS THAN 5.5 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 16 PERCENT WATER
column168: FREIGHT SHIFTED IN TRANSIT CRUSHING 3 CTNS.  ONLY 1-1 GALLON JUG WAS FOUND DAMAED WHICH CAUSED LEAKAGE.  THE ENTRIE CONTNETS OF THE JUG HAD LEAKED OUT AND HAD DRIED UPON ARRIVAL AT MMT.  THE OTHER CARTONS WERE DAMAGED BUT NONE WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE FREIGHT WAS SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE PER ROBERT WELCH AT SEARS.  THIS WAS RETURNED FREIGHT FROM SEARS FROM SUMMER MDSE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: SECURITY GUARD ON PATROL NOTED MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OF RAILCAR, AND REPORTED INCIDENT TO THE RAILROAD.  UNION PACIFIC SPECIAL AGENT DECHANT INSPECTED TANK CAR, NOTING THAT THE MATERIAL WAS SLOWLY DRIPPING FROM AN 18-INCH LONG UNLOADING CONNECTION THREADED INTO THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  TIGHTENING OF THE CONNECTION STOPPED THE LEAK COMPLETELY.  LEAKAGE RATE WAS SUFFICIENTLY SLOW TO ALLOW EVAPORATION OF MATERIAL FROM SURFACE OF THE BALLAST BELOW THE RAILCAR.  NO CLEANUP WAS WARRENTED.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THE EMERY WORLDWIDE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED OF A SPILL ON OCT 22 AT 0215L.  SHIPMENT WAS FOUND WITH A WET CORNER, A VERY STRONG ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  SHIPMENT WAS NOT LABELED, MARKED, OR IN A SPEC BOX.  SHIPMENT HAD NO VISIBLE DAMANGE.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LID HAD POPPED OFF.  WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  CHRIS MOUSER.

THE DRUMS WERE ON OUR NON-CONVEYABLE BELT WHEN IT WAS NOTICED THA THE INK WAS COING OUT FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  IT WAS RIGHT WHERE THE HANDLE TO THE DRUM WAS.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THAT WE FORWARD THE MATERIAL TO THE CONSIGNEE.

DURING THE OFF LOAD THE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE AREA ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM WHERE THE HANDLE IS PLACED.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SIGN OF DAMAGE TO THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AFTER IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND WE ARE WAITING FOR A DISPOSITION.

AS THE PACKAGE WAS BEING UNLOADED WE NOTICED FUMES EMINATING FROM THE BOX. THE BOX WAS OPENED AND WE FOUND THE CAP TO THE BOTTLE TO BE LOOSE AND THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT.  WE REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE SORT, PLACED IT IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.  WE ARE WAITING FOR A DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE CONTAINED GLASS BOTTLES INSIDE FIBREBOARD BOX, DIVIDED WITH FIBREBOARD PARTITIONS.  DAMAGE APPARENTLY DUE TO PACKAGE BEING DROPPED NO EXTERNAL DAMGE TO OUTER-FIBREBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT MATERIAL IN THE BOX.  PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM & THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: LEAKAGE APPARENTLY DUE TO SMALL PUNCUTRE, NEAR TOP OF DRUM.  CAUSE/ORIGIN OF PUNCTURE IS UNKNOWN.  PACKAGE PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM & SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE FELL OF BELT, APPROX 2-3 FT, DURING SORT.  CRIMP TOP LID CAME OFF AND ENTIRE CONTENTS SPILLED FROM DRUM.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM CONCRETE WITH ABSORBANT POWDER, PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM (S) AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

AS THE DRUM WAS BEING UNLOADED IT WAS DROPPED FROM A HEIGHT OF APPROXIMATELY THREE(3) FEET.  UPON NOTICING THE LEAK, THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC DOCUMENT SORT BAG AND THEN INTO A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH MAGIC SORB.  THE SHIPPE WAS CALLED AND REQUESTED THAT WE RETURN THE ORIGINAL DRUM, WHICH WE HAVE DONE.

AS THE DANGEROUS GOODS UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT WE REMOVED THE DOOR TO INSPECT THE FREIGHT.  UPON DOING SO WE NOTICED THAT THIS PACKAGE WAS LEAKING.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE BOX WAS OPENED AND THE INNER GLASS BOTTLES WERE OUND TO HAVE LOOSE SCREW CAPS.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ARE WAITING FOR A DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE WAS INSPECTED DUE TO STRONG ODORS.  INTERNAL PACKAGE INSPECTION DETERMINED APPROXIMATELY 3 OZS HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE TOP.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE CONTAINER CAPS WERE DEFECTIVE OR THE CONTAINERS WERE FILLED TOO FULL.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIIED WHO AUTHORIZED THE CONTAINER TO BE PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE RECIPIENT.

PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATION BECAUSE OF VERY SLIGHT LEAKAGE FROM THE TOP WHICH EVIDENTLY WAS LOOSE.  THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY CONTAINED AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

THE DRUMS WERE EMITTING ODORS.  UPON OPENING THE BOXES WE FOUND TWO DRUMS WITH LOOSE TOPS.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM EACH DRUM. THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND THE PACKAGE WAS FORWARDED TO THE RECIPIENT.

WHEN THE PACKAGES WERE BEING INSPECTED, THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST NOTICED FUMES COMING FROM THE BOSES.  THE BOXES WERE OPENED AND WE FOUND BOTH INNER CONTAINERS TO HAVE LEAKED.  ALL CONTENTS WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE BOXES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SORT.  PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM, AND HELD FOR A DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHEN THE PACKAGES WERE BEING INSPECTED, THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST NOTICED FUMES COMING FROM THE BOSES.  THE BOXES WERE OPENED AND WE FOUND BOTH INNER CONTAINERS TO HAVE LEAKED.  ALL CONTENTS WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE BOXES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SORT.  PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM, AND HELD FOR A DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: AS THE PACKAGES WERE BEING INSPECTED, FUMES WERE NOTICED COMING FROM THE BOXES.  THE BOXES WERE OPENED AND BOTH METAL CANS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE BOXES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND PLACED IN STEEL SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND THE PACKAGES RETURNED.

THE BOX WAS DROPPED WHILE IT WAS BEING SORTED.  THE CONTENTS BEGAN BEAKING OUT OF IT.  WE IMMEDIATELY PLACED THE BOX IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND BLEACHED THE SPILLED AREA.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE GOING FOR DIAGONISTIC TESTING.  I ALSO NOTIFIED THE CENTERS FOR DISEASE CONTROL.  THE FAA DUTY OFFICER WAS NOTIFIED AT 0056 HRS CDT ON 10-30-93.  THE PACKAGE DOES NOT APPEAR TO HAVE ENOUGH ABSORBANT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE.

THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN A BROKEN GLASS NOISE WAS HEARD COMING FROM INSIDE THE BOX.  UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND ONE BROWN GLASS BOTTLE WITH THE BOTTOM OF THE BOTTLE ROKEN COMPLETELY.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND WE ARE WAITING FOR A DISPOSITION.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: UNMARKED, UNLABELLED BOX. INNER PACKAGINGS INCLUDED 2 GLASS BOTTLES & 2 GLASS BOTTLES & 2 AEROSOL CANS.  ONE GLASS BOTTLE LEAKED.  PACKED USING STYROFOAM PEANUTS FOR CUSHIONING MATERIAL.  FAA WAS CONTACTED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: METAL CAN APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED DUE TO INTERNAL PRESSURE.  NO MAKRINGS/LABELS/DOCUMENTATION.  NEWSPAPER WAS USED AS CUSHIONING/ABSORBANT MATERIAL.  PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM;  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED.

WHILE AT TRUCK STOP, OUR DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING.  HE PLACED A CONTAINER UNDER THE DRIP AND CALLED COMPANY PERSONNEL.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE LOAD INTO ANOTHER UNIT.  ONE THE TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED, OUR DRIVER CONTINUED TO HIS DESTINATION.  THE LEAKING TANK WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR REPAIRS.

PRESSURE IN CUSTOMER'S LINE BUILT UP AND BLEW 2 QUARTS OF PRODUCT ON OUR DRIVER.  WE HAD NO STARTED TO UNLOAD;  THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES WERE CLOSED AND THERE WAS NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED AND REMOVED BY THE CUSTOMER.

AFTER UNLOADING, OUR DRIVER UNHOOKED THE HOSE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S LINE. SINCE THERE WAS NO SHUT OFF VALVE IN THE CUSTOMER'S LINE, OUR DRIVER RECONNECTED HIS HOSE.  CUSTOMER PERSONNEL WASHED THE SPILLED PRODUCT DOWN THEIR RECOVERY DRAIN.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: 5 DRUMS WERE LOADED ON PALLETS, STRETCH WRAPPED AND TIED TOGETHER WITH TWIN.  AFTER 50 MILES FROM LOADING SITE AND WITHIN 1 MILE FROM TERMINAL. DRIVER MADE AN EMERGENCY STOP TO AVOID COLLISION.  DRUM OVERTURNED AND BUNG CAME OUT DUE TO IMPROPER BUNG. (SMALLER DIAMETER THAN OPENING).

column168: TRAILER OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING WHILE ON LOT AFTER UNLOADING FROM INBOUND TRAIN.  ATSF RESPONDER LOCATED SINGLE POLY DRUM OF ACID AS CAUSE OF LEAK. DRUM WAS PINCHED BETWEEN TWO PALLETS IN THE LOAD RESULTING IN CRUSHED BOTTOM SIDE.  DRUM PLACED IN OVERPACK AND PRODUCT, VAN AND GROUND SPILLS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  LOAD WAS ADJUSTED AND RELEASED AFTER DECONTAMINATION.

column168: CAR FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP DURING ROUTINE TRAINYARD INSPECTION.  ATSF RESPONDER FOUND TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE LOOSE VALVE WAS CLOSED WITH 3/4 TURN. BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS ALSO TIGHTENED. ACTUAL LOSS OF PRODUCT IS LIKELY MORE ACCOUNT HIGH RATE OF EVAPORATION.

TANK CONTAINER FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT IN-GATE INSPECTION TO ENTER RAIL FACILITY.  TAKE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  SHIPPERS HAZ MAT TEAM (MILES CHEMICAL) RESPONDED TO INCIDENT.  TEAM REPLACED PRESSURE VALUE AND GASKET.  PRODUCT ON TANK CONTAINER WAS WASHED CLEAN.  LOAD FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: LOCAL CREW FOUND TANK CAR TO BE LEAKING FROM TOP MANWAY AREA.  ATSF RESPONDER DETERMINED LEAK TO BE FROM MANWAY'S QUICK FILL HOLE.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO MAKE REPAIRS.  TOSCO RESPONDER FOUND DETERIORATED GASKET AND UNEVEN SEALING SURFACE AT MANWAY FILL HOLE.  OLD GASKET WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED, SEALING SURFACE WAS SCRAPPED CLEAN.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND SIDES OF CAR WASHED.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

CAR FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION.  ATSF RESPONDER DETERMINED PROBLEMS TO BE PARTIALLY OPEN UNLOADING VALVE AND ALSO PARTIALLY OPEN BOTTOM OPERATED OUTLET VALVE.  RESPONDER CLOSED VALVES AND CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

CAR FOUND TO BE LEAKING AFTER ARRIVAL IN TRAINYARD FOR ROUTINE INSPECTION. ATSF RESPONDER DETERMINED LEAK TO BE FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING MOUNTING FLANGE.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIR, WHICH CONSISTED OF TIGHTENING TWO 11/16" SECUREMENT NUTS.
DOME GASKET NOT BIG ENOUGH, CAUSING SPILL.  GASKETS WERE REPLACED.

INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN INTERCHANGED TO THE GEORGIA SOUTHWESTERN RAILWAY FROM NORFOLK SOUTHERN.  G.S.W. THEN PLACED THE CAR FOR UNLOADING AND THE CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE NOTIFIED THE G.S.W. THAT THE CAR WAS BEING REJECTED DUE TO EVIDENCE OF RECENT LEAKAGE.  THE G.S.W. RAILWAY THEN PULLED THE CAR AND RETURNED IT TO NORFOLK SOUTHERN IN A CUT OF CARS.  NORFOLK SOUTHERN HAD NO PRIOR NOTIFICATION OR KNOWLEDGE OF THIS CAR LEAKING.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO REPLACE A DEFECTIVE SAFETY VENT DISC AND HOUSING.  CAR WAS THEN SAFE FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON I-75 AROUND THE 65 MILE MARKET WHEN A DRIVER BEHIND HIM INFORMED HIM THAT SOMETHING WAS LEAKING OUT THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER PULLED OVER AT THE 66 MILE MARKER AND RAISED THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER TO FIND CORROSIVE LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF A PORTABLE TANK. VARIOUS AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. THE DRAIN VALVE WAS SHUT OFF AND A CAP SCREWED ON THE VALVE OPENING TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD HAVE USED PROTECTIVE DUNNAGE AROUND THE DRAIN VALVE SO THAT THE HANDLE WOULD NOT HAVE A CHANCE TO OPEN. THERE WAS NO PLUG IN THE DRAIN VALVE. RECOMMEND THAT DRAIN VALVES ON PORTABLE TANKS HAVE A SAFETY PIN LOCK ON THE HANDLE TO PREVENT IT FROM OPENING DURING TRANSPORTATION.

WHILE UNLOADING, VALVE ON PIPE CRACKED.  DRIVER WAS UNLOADING FROM A RAILCAR.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN UNLOADING AREA AND NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.
DRIVER THOUGHT VALVE ON CUSTOMERS TANK WAS OPEN WHEN IT WAS CLOSED. PRESSURE CAUSED HOSE TO BLOW WHILE UNLOADING SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.

A SKID FELL AGAINST THE DRUM, CAUSING A PINHOLE IN THE SIDE DURING TRANSIT.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND PATCHED.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND DISPOSAL WAS HANDLED BY ENVIROCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL, 1005 INVESTMENT BLVD., APEX, N.C. 27502.  INSTRUCTION WAS GIVEN IN PROPER LOADING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN RELATION TO ACCOMPANYING FREIGHT.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEANED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION.  THE RECEIVER INDICATED THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM IN THE STORAGE TANK TO ACCEPT THE MATERIAL BEING DELIVERED.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED.  OUR DRIVER STOPPED THE UNLOADING PROCESS BUT PRODUCT SPILLED FROM THE CUSTOMER'S SPILL LINE BEFORE IT WAS CAPPED.  THE CUSTOMER TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.  PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION AND WENT INTO THE BREAK ROOM.  WHILE THERE, THE UNLOADER CAME OUT AND PROCEEDED TO SAMPLE THE PRODUCT.  WHEN HE REMOVED THE CAP, PRODUCT SPLASHED ON HIM.  HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVES TO STOP THE SPILL.  HE WAS TREATED IN FIRST AID.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP ON THE UNLOADING PAID BY THE CUSTOMER.
PRESSURE BUILT UP AND BLEW END OF HOSE OFF.  PRODUCT SPILLED IN CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS PUT IN DRUMS AND WILL DISPOSE OF PRODUCT.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN PD 2. ONE OF THE FIVE GALLON CANS HAD A FAULTY CAP. THE CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED AND THE TOTAL PACKAGE WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON THE PD-6, DOOR #176 LEAKING. 2 OF 4 BOTTLES WERE BROKEN. THE BROKEN BOTTLES WERE DISCARDED AND REMAINDER DELIVERED. THE BROKEN BOTTLES WERE DISCARDED FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE. TWO EMPLOYEES WERE INJURED WHEN A VENT, IN WHICH THE DAMAGED PACKAGE HAD LEAKED, AUTOMATICALLY TURNED ON. MIST WAS BLOWN BACK INTO THEIR FACES. BOTH INDIVIDUALS IMMEDIATELY WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WHERE THEY WERE IMMEDIATELY TREATED AND RELEASED WITH NO WORK RESTRICTIONS. A COPY OF THIS REPORT IS BEING SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT CUSTOMER SERVICE ACCOUNT EXECUTIVE FOR FOLLOW UP.

column168: (MTPL A)  AT ABOUT 1410 HOURS ON 10/28/93, A NORTHBOUND KCS TRAIL DERAILED EIGHT (8) CARS FROM THE MAIN LINE AT KCS MILEPOST 691.6, JUST SOUTH OF DERIDDER, LA. THIS CAR, GATX 22297, WAS TURNED OVER AND LADING WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE HATCH COVER AT AN ESTIMATED RATE OF ONE GPH.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED ON THE HATCH COVER WHICH REDUCED THE FLOW OF LADING.  THE CAR WAS UP-RIGHTED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK, AT 0845 HOURS ON 10/29/93.  IT WAS DECIDED TO TRANSFER THE LADING INTO TRUCKS TO EXPEDITE THE REMOVAL.  IT WAS DURING THIS TRANSFER THAT A HOSE BURST, SPRAYING LADING ON A CONTRACTOR AND ON THE GROUND. THE CONTRACTOR WAS DECONTAMINATED ON SITE AND TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL.  HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED BACK TO THE SITE WITHIN ONE HOUR.  MAINLINE OPERATIONS WERE RESTORED ON 10/29/93 AT ABOUT 1300 HOURS. TRANSFER, NOW INTO RAIL CARS, RESUMED AFTER WEATHER DELAYS AND WAS COMPLETED ON 11/2/93 AT 0115 HOURS.  ALL CARS INVOLVED WERE REMOVED FROM SITE ON 11/4/93 AT 0115 HOURS.  ALL CARS INVOLVED WERE REMOVED FROM SITE ON 11/4/93 AT 1845 HOURS.  THE DECONTAIMATED/CLEANUP PHASE BEGAN ALMOST IMMEDIATELY.  THE PROCESS OF TESTING AND REMEDIATION WAS COMPLETED IN COORDINATION WITH THE LA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  THE CLOSURE REPORT WAS SUBMITTED TO THE LADEQ AND ALL CONCERNED ON 12/7/93.               (MTPL B)  AT ABOUT 1410 HOURS ON 10/28/93, A NORTHBOUND KCS TRAIN DERAILED EIGHT (8) CARS FROM THE MAIN LINE AT KCS MILEPOST 691.6, JUST SOUTH OF DERIDDER, LA.  THIS CAR, GATX 47362, WAS OVERTURNED.  THIS CAR DEVELOPED A SLIGHT DRIP FROM THE SAFETY VENT AS A RESULT OF THE RUPTURE DISK FAILING FROM THE PRESSURE OF THE INVERTED MATERIAL IN THE CAR. THE CAR WAS UP-RIGHTED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK, AT 0845 HOURS ON 10/29/93. THE CONTENTS OF THIS CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO RAIL CARS, AND WAS COMPLETED AT 0115 HOURS ON 11/2/93. MAINLINE OPERATIONS WERE RESTORED ON 10/29/93 AT ABOUT 1300 HOURS. ALL CARS INVOLVED WERE REMOVED FROM SITE ON 11/4/93 AT 1845 HOURS.

HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED BACK TO THE SITE WITHIN ONE HOUR.  MAINLINE OPERATIONS WERE RESTORED ON 10/29/93 AT ABOUT 1300 HOURS. TRANSFER, NOW INTO RAIL CARS, RESUMED AFTER WEATHER DELAYS AND WAS COMPLETED ON 11/2/93 AT 0115 HOURS.  ALL CARS INVOLVED WERE REMOVED FROM SITE ON 11/4/93 AT 0115 HOURS.  ALL CARS INVOLVED WERE REMOVED FROM SITE ON 11/4/93 AT 1845 HOURS.  THE DECONTAIMATED/CLEANUP PHASE BEGAN ALMOST IMMEDIATELY.  THE PROCESS OF TESTING AND REMEDIATION WAS COMPLETED IN COORDINATION WITH THE LA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  THE CLOSURE REPORT WAS SUBMITTED TO THE LADEQ AND ALL CONCERNED ON 12/7/93.               (MTPL B)  AT ABOUT 1410 HOURS ON 10/28/93, A NORTHBOUND KCS TRAIN DERAILED EIGHT (8) CARS FROM THE MAIN LINE AT KCS MILEPOST 691.6, JUST SOUTH OF DERIDDER, LA.  THIS CAR, GATX 47362, WAS OVERTURNED.  THIS CAR DEVELOPED A SLIGHT DRIP FROM THE SAFETY VENT AS A RESULT OF THE RUPTURE DISK FAILING FROM THE PRESSURE OF THE INVERTED MATERIAL IN THE CAR. THE CAR WAS UP-RIGHTED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK, AT 0845 HOURS ON 10/29/93. THE CONTENTS OF THIS CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO RAIL CARS, AND WAS COMPLETED AT 0115 HOURS ON 11/2/93. MAINLINE OPERATIONS WERE RESTORED ON 10/29/93 AT ABOUT 1300 HOURS. ALL CARS INVOLVED WERE REMOVED FROM SITE ON 11/4/93 AT 1845 HOURS.

SHE ANSWERED YES, I THEN ASKED IF SHE WAS SURE EVERYTHING WAS HOOKED UP BECAUSE I WAS GOING TO FILL THE TANK.  SHE SAID SHE WAS SURE IT WAS, BUT WENT TO ASK SOMEONE IN THE OTHER END OF THE HOUSE.  UPON RETURNING SHE SAID IT WAS AND THE EVERYTHING WORKED FINE BECAUSE THEY HAD BEEN USING THE FURNALE.  I SAID OK AND THANK YOU, AND TO PREVENT WATER FROM ENERING THE SYSTEM.  SHE SAID OK , THANKS FOR POINTING THAT OUT. CLOSED DOOR.  I RETURNED TO MY TRUCK, INSENTED METER TICKET, PULLED HOSE TO FILL LOCATION AND STARTED TO FILL AS WITH OTHER FILLS LIKE THIS.  IT WAS SLOW, AFTER WHAT SEEMED APPROX. 15 MINUTES FILL PIPE BEGAN TO FILL UP.  I STOPPED AND RETURNED TO MY TRUCK.  FILLED OUT TICKET FOR 214 GALLONS, PLACED IT IN ENVELOPE AND PLACED IT ON FRONT DOOR.  LEFT FOR MY NEXT DELIVERY.  APPROX. 12:30 - 1:00 THE DISPATCHER CALLED ME ON THE RAPID AND ASKED IF I HAD DELIVERED TO 1134 14H AVE.  I TOLD HIM I DID.  HE THEN ASKED IF ANYTHING SEEMED UNUSUAL WHILE DOING SO.  I TOLD HIM WHAT IS STATED IN THE STATEMENT ABOVE.  HE SAID OK THANKS.  I RETURNED TO THE PLANT AND HAD LUNCH.

THE SHIPMENT HAD A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL ON THE SIDE.  THERE WAS NO PROPER SHIPPING NAME ON THE BOX. NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANAGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING IT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A DOT 12B40 FIBREBOARD BOX. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WERE 6 X 32 FLUID OUNCE METAL CANS.  THESE METAL CANS HAD SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  THERE WERE NO OTHER MEANS TO SECURE HE CLOSURES.  ONE OF THESE METAL CANS LEAKED APPROXIMATLEY 2 OUNCES OF ISOPROPANOL DUE TO THE CLOSURE COMING LOOSE.  THE UN NUMBER WAS ON THE BOX NEXT TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD IN ILN DUE TO NEEDING SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING THE RECEIPT OF PROPER DOCUMENTATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE REPACKED IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

BELOW THE DISC WAS A HALF PIPE SPLASH BAFFLE.  ROBINSON ALSO NOTED THAT ONE OF THE CORNER PLUGS ON THE SPLASH DEFLECTOR WAS MISSING.  ROBINSON CONTACTED MR. HARRY LLOYD PERSONNEL MANAGER FOR GEORGIA GULF AND MR. FRANK VENDT, SHIPPING SUPERVISOR.  VENDT DISPATCHED MR. JIMMY SMITH AND MR. ALVIN LEMOINE TO REPLACE THE DISC.  LEMOINE AND SMITH REPLACED THE DISC WITHOUT INCIDENT. GEORGIA GULF REQUESTED THAT THE CAR BE RETURNED TO THE PLANT AT PLAQUEMINE SO THAT THE DRYED LADING COULD BE SAFELY REMOVED AND THE SPLASHED DEFLECTOR REPLACED.  THE CAR WAS RESPOTTED AT GEORGIA GULF(ALLEMANIA) AT 1755 HOURS OF 10/07/93 WITH OUT INCIDENT.

WHILE INSPECTING THE ON HAND GSX IN THE OFFICE I NOTICED A SMALL BOX FOR COLUMBIA INSPECTION INC A/W BILL 1395-0182. THE CONTENTS ON THE A/W BILL INDICATED IT CONTAINED "PARTS". I PICKED UP THE BOX & SHOOK IT AND COULD HEAR LIQUID INSIDE, NOT SURE OF THE CONTENTS, I OPENED THE BOX TO FIND 2 METAL QUART CONTAINER. THEY WERE EACH WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND SMELLED LIKE GASOLINE OR SOME SORT OF SOLVENT. 1.  CONTENTS OF PKG WAS FALSIFIED. 2. CONTENTS OF PKG WAS A DANGEROUS GOOD GSX WAS SHIPPED FROM LAS/SEA ON AS 623 CNX IN SEA ON 2073 SEA/PDX. CC: JIM COOK AS AIRLINES, NW AIRLINES. ON ARRIVAL I FOUND OUT AN INCIDENT REPORT IN RELATION TO THE ABOVE GOLDSTREAK SAME WAY ISSUE BY TRACY MILLER. I CALLED SUPERVISOR TO LET HER KNOW AND SUGESTED TO HER (KRISTY) THAT WE SHOULD FOLLOW UP THIS, DOING SOME CHECKING WITH NW LAS AS TO WHY THEY WROTE PARTS IN THE CONTENTS BOX INSTEAD OF THE NATURAL CONTENTS WHICH WAS DISEL FUEL. PEDRO GONZALEZ WHEN CONSIGNEE ARR TO PICKUP WE OPENED IT. CONTENTS ON AWB AND I CALLED LASFF AND SPOKE TO TIM HE WAS AT THE OFFICE WHEN THE SHIPPER ORIGINALLY BROUGHT THE FUEL CANS IN TO BE SHIPPED. THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED THAT FUEL COULD NOT BE SHIPPED ON THE PSGR PLANE. THE SHIPPER WENT AWAY AND CAME BACK A SHORT TIME LATER WITH A BOX. THE AGENT WHO HELPED HIM ASKED TO EXAMINE THE BOX AND THE SHIPPER REFUED. THE AGENT THEN REFUSED TO ACCEPT THE SHIPMENT. I CALLED AND SPOKE TO A LADY AGENT AT THE LASNW TICKET CTR-SHE WAS WORKING WITH THE COUNTER AGENT WHO ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT. WHE SAID THE SHIPPER ADVISED THE CTR AGENT THAT FREIGHT HAD SENT BECAUSE IT WAS TO CLOSE TO FLIGHT DEPARTURE THE AGENT ACCEPTED THE PACKAGE AND SENT IT OUT. I REQUESTED THAT THE NW CTR AGENT PLEASE WRITE AN INCIDENT REPORT OF WHAT HE REMEMBERS OF THE TRANSACTION AND SEND IT TO US AT PDXLLQX. I ALSO ASKED TIM AT THE FREIGHT OFFICE TO DO THE SAME.

ON 10/21/93, I, RANDY WILLIAMS, P/T HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, RECIEVED A CALL VIA RADIO FROM MY DISPATCH OFFICE THAT SORT SUPERVISOR, DAN ECKLE, HAD REPORTED A SPILL OF A GRAY LIQUID, WITH AN ODOR COMING FROM AN EXPRESS PACK ENVELOPE. THE CALL CAME IN AT 00:56 HRS. IN BLDG A AT OUR FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. UPON ARRIVAL I FOUND INSIDE OF A BAG OF EXPRESS FREIGHT, ONE EXPRESS PACK ENVELOPE THAT HAD A GRAY LIQUID LEAKING AND THE ODOR WAS POSSIBLY THAT OF INK. THE LEAKING EXPRESS PACK ENVELOPE WAS REMOVED FROM THE BAG OF EXPRESS CONTAINING OTHER ENVELOPES, AND ALL RESIDUE WAS REMOVED FROM THEM.  THE LETTER EXPRESS ENVELOPE WAS OPENED AND INSIDE A 1 PINT WIDE MOUTH METAL RECEPTACLE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THE METAL RECEPTACLE HAD A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WITH TAPE AROUND THE CLOSURE THAT WAS USED TO SECURE THE LID IN PLACE. EVIDENTLY, DUE TO THE LEAKAGE, THE TAPE FAILED TO HOLD THE CLOSURE IN PLACE, THUS ALLOWING THE INNER RECEPTACLE TO LEAK ITS CONTENTS.  ALSO, NOTED WAS THAT THERE WASN'T ANY ABSORBANT OR CUSHIONING MATERIAL USED AND THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS FOUND ON THE OUTER OR INNER PACKAGINGS TO INDICATE THAT THE LIQUID WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION IT WAS NOTED THAT THE AIR WAYBILL DID NOT INDICATE THE INNER CONTENTS AND NO OTHER DOCUMENTATION ACCOMPANIED THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND WAS SECURED UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN OUR SECURITY CAGE PENDING  FAA INVESTIGATION. NOTE: SPECIAL AGENT JOHN BECKIUS OF THE INDIANAPOLIS FAA CASFU OFFICE ARRIVED AT OUR FACILITY ON 10/22/93 AND TOOK POSSESSION OF THE ABOVE SHIPMENT FOR ANALYSIS.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: PACKAGE WAS PART OF A DELIVERY COURIER'S LOAD IN THE RALEIGH, NORTH CAROLINA AREA. THE COURIER WAS DELIVERING THE PACKAGE WHEN HE NOTICED PURPLISH STAINS ON SOME OF THE PACKAGES IN HIS LOAD. THE COURIER THOUGHT AT THE TIME THAT IT WAS SOME SORT OF FRUIT JUICE THAT HAD SOMEHOW BEEN SPILLED ON THE PACKAGES. AFTER HE FINISHED HIS DELIVERIES HE REPORTED HIS FINDINGS TO REGGIE WARREN, A DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST AT THE STATION WHO DECIDED TO INVESTIGATE FURTHER. AFTER REGGIE CALLED THE SHIPPER AND THE RECIPIENT THE SUBSTANCE WAS SUSPECTED TO BE POTASSIUM PERMANGANATE, AN OXIDIZING SUBSTANCE THATS REGULATED. AS HEAVY RAINS OCCURED THE DAY OF DELIVERLY THE SUBSTANCE WHEN IT GETS WET HAS A PURPLISH APPEARANCE. RALEIGH F.A.A. WAS CONTACTED AND SPECIAL AGENT ROBERT ROWLAND WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. I TOLD HIM THAT I SUSPECTED THERE WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZ SHIPMENT THAT WAS DISCOVERED AND THAT I HAD  TALKED TO A COSTAS GOUNARAKIS AT THE DESTINATION LOCATION WHO SUSPECTED THAT THE ORIGIN LOCATION INADVERTENDLY SHIPPED THE COMMODITY BY AIR WHEN IT SHOULD HAVE GONE BY GROUND TRANSPORATION. THE COMMODITY IS NOT REGULATED ACCORDING TO MR. GOUNARAKIS SO CONSEQUENTLY THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPING CERTIFICATIONS ASSOCIATION WITH THE SHIPMENT THE F.A.A. IS INVESTIGATING.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN LEAKAGE FROM AN INNER APPARENTLY COMPROMISED THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX CAUSING THE BOX TO BREAK OPEN.  THE BOX WAS TAKEN TO THE REWRAP AREA AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE AEROSOL CANS WERE IN THE BOX. A HOUSEHOLD LIQUID DETERGENT WAS THE INNER CONTAINER THAT LEAKED WHICH WAS THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE PROBLEM.  THE PACKAGE AND ITS CONTENTS WERE HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE F.A.A.  THE F.A.A. INSPECTED THE PACKAGE ON 10/27.  THE PACKAGE WAS RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED A DG SPILL SPECIALIST WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SECONDARY SORT BELT 18 DEAL WITH THE SPILL. HE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND ONE OF THE INNER CONTAINERS DID NOT HAVE A TOP ON IT. AS THE BOX WAS HANDLED THIS IS WHAT CAUSED THE SPILL TO OCCUR. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPING CERTIFICATION ASSOCIATED WITH THIS PACKAGE. I COMMUNICATED WITH A REPRESENTATIVE FOR THE SHIPPER, RON WASILEWSKI WHO SENT THE ATTACHED MSDS ON THE COMMODITY. THE PACKAGE IS BEING IN THE HUB PENDING NOTIFICATION TO F.A.A.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: ON 10/08/93, AT 0230, NIGHT OPS SORT SUPERVISOR DAN DUTEIL REPORTED A SPILL AT OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED IN SECONDARY 8, DIVERTER 9, BROWN LIQUID, NO ODOR, ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT ON FINGER, NO REACTION, NO MEDICAL ATTENTION NECESSARY, NO ACCIDENT REPORT FILED.  CERT II, FRAN VANCE HAZ MAT COORDINATOR AND CERT 14, RANDY WILLIAMS PARTTIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX LEAKING A THICK BROWN LIQUID.  THIS LIQUID WAS FOUND TO BE "WELD WOOD NONFLAMMABLE CONTACT CEMENT".  THE CEMENT WAS PACKAGED IN 1 GALLON METAL CONTAINERS, 4 CONTAINERS PER BOX.  THE CONTAINERS HAD FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES WITH NO MEANS TO SECURE.  NO ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS ENCLOSED WITH THIS SHIPMENT.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO THE INNER CONTAINERS BEING CRUSHED THROUGH THE SORTING PROCESS, AND THE CLOSURES DID NOT REMAIN IN PLACE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG AND HELD FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR CONFIRMATION OF CONTENTS.  THIS IS A 3 PIECE SHIPMENT, THE REMAINING PIECES WERE RETREIVED FROM THE SORTING AREA.  ALL THREE PIECES ARE BEING HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SORT UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM MSDS AND POSSIBLE FAA INVESTIGATION. THE HAZ MAT SPILL TEAM CLEARED THE SCENE AT 0247.  A MESSAGE WAS SENT TO THE SHIPPER FOR THE MSDS.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED AND THE INFORMATION ON THE MSDS INDICATES THIS TRICHLOROETHANE SOLUTION, 6.1, UN2831, PKG GP III.  A COPY OF THE MSDS WILL BE INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AWAITING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA. PACKAGE INFORMATION IS AS FOLLOWS: ALL THREE BOXES ARE IDENTICAL IN MARKINGS AND ATTACHMENTS.  TOP: MARKINGS: THIS SIDE UP, 784M2D, ABX AIR WAYBILL, 46#, (PACKAGE NUMBER FOR THE PACKAGE THAT LEAKED) 1 OF 3. ATTACHMENTS: "PICKING TICKET" (SAME AS A PURCHASE ORDER) A COPY OF THIS DOCUMENT WILL BE INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT.  SIDE 1: MARKINGS: CONTENTS 4 - 1 GALLON, PLEASE ROTATE STOCK.  ATTACHMENTS: NONE  SIDE 2: MARKINGS: NONFLAMMABLE CONTACT CEMENT (2000), 4 - 1 GALLON UPC 0517, DAP INC, DAYTON, OH 45401  ATTACHMENTS: NONE  SIDE 3: MARKINGS: SHIP TO (NOTHING ENTERED), 4 - 1 GALLON  ATTACHMENTS: NONE  SIDE 4: NO MARKINGS OR ATTACHMENTS   BOTTOM: MARKINGS: 69581 ROUND, MANUFACTURES SEAL, LEWISBURG CONTAINER CO., LEWISBURG, OHIO BURSTING TEST 175 LBS PER SQ INCH, MIN COMB WT FACINGS 75 LBS, SIZE LIMIT 60 INCHES, GROSS WT LT 40 LBS.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ASCCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

ON 10/15/93, AT 02:15AM, NIGHT OPS SORT SUPERVISOR ANDY HOLMES REPORTED A SPILL AT OUR SORT FACILITY BLDG. "C" PRIMARY-B-DIVERTER NUMBER 22, CLEAR LIQUID WITH AN ODOR OF "ROTTEN EGGS" AND 12 PEOPLE IN CONTACT BY WAY OF INHALATION, AND THEY HAD BEEN MOVED OUT OF THE AREA WHERE THE ODOR COULD NO LONGER BE DETECTED.  NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES SHOWED ANY SIGNS OR SYMPTOMS FROM EXPOSURE, NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED, THEREFORE NO ACCIDENT REPORT WAS FILLED.  AT 02:18 AM, CERT. 3 BEN TAYLOR, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, AND CERT 16 JON MOOTS, PART TIME HAZ MAT MAT COORDINATOR, AND CERT 16 JON MOOTS, PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL WE DETECTED THE ODOR AND DONNED CARTRIDGE MASKS AND BEGAN TESTING THE LIQUID ON THE SLIDE AREAS WITH PYHYDRION PH PAPER AND FOUND A READING OF PH +12 WHICH INDICATED A CAUSTIC SUBSTANCE, AND WOULD FALL UNDER THE DOT REGULATIONS AS A CORROSIVE LIQUID.  DUE TO TIME RESTRAINTS ADDITIONAL P/T HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS WERE CALLED TO ASSIST THE CLEAN-UP AND NEUTRALIZING OF THE SLIDE AREAS THAT WERE AFFECTED.  THE PACKAGE WAS LOCATED, BUT DUE TO THE LEAKAGE AND TAPE AROUND THE PACKAGE IT WAS HARD TO OBTAIN ANY INFORMATION AS TO THE CONTENTS.  THE AIRWAYBILL DID NOT HAVE ANY DESCRIPTION AS TO WHAT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE.  INSIDE OF THE BOX WAS TWO GLASS BOTTLES APPROXIMATELY 7 OUNCES EACH, ONE OF WHICH WAS BROKEN DURING THE SORTING PROCESS.  ONCE THE SHIPMENT WAS FOUND IT WAS PLACED IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND HELD FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET IN OUR HAZ MAT SORT CAGE, UNTIL VERIFICATION OF CONTENTS COULD BE CONFIRMED.  THE HAZ MAT SPILL TEAM CLEARED THE SCENE AT 02:52 AM.  A MESSAGE WAS SENT TO THE ORIGINATING AIRBORNE EXPRESS STATION, REQUESTING THAT THEY CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS).  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED AND LISTS THIS PRODUCT AS: CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. UN1760 PG II. (ALKANOLAMINE).  A COPY OF THE MANUFACTURE'S MSDS WILL BE INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT.  THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION IS BEING STORED IN OUR CORROSIVE STORAGE CABINET UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE FROM THE INVESTIGATING FAA AGENT. UPON RELEASE THE SHIPMENT WILL BE EITHER FORWARDED OR RETURNED IN A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM UNLESS SPECIFICALLY REQUESTED TO BE DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO STATE AND LOCAL REGULATIONS.  OUTER PACKAGE INFORMATION: THE ONLY MARKINGS THAT ARE SOMEWHAT LEGIBLE INDICATE THAT THE BOX ORIGINALLY CONTAINED SAFETY GOGGLES, BY THE WORDS "ENCON EYE PROTECTION 160, CHEMICAL SPLASH/IMPACT GOGGLES"  DIMS: 7" IN LENGTH X 4" WIDE X 3" HIGH AND IS APPROX. LM THICK.  AIRBORNE EXPRESS AIRWAYBILL.  (NO DESCRIPTION OF CONTENTS LISTED.)  INNER PACKAGE INFORMATION: 2 X 8 OUNCE CLEAR GLASS BOTTLES (1 OF WHICH WAS BROKEN) CONTAINED A BROWNISH GREEN OILY SUBSTANCE APPROX. 7 OZS. EACH.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL USEDD: NONE  CUSHIONING MATERIAL USED: 2 STRIPS OF A FOAM LIKE MATERIAL , DIMS APPROX. 6 1/2 IN. LONG, 1/2 IN. THICK AND 1 1/2 IN. WIDE  NOTE: EACH BOTTLE HAD BEEN WRAPPED IN A THIN WHITE FOAM LIKE MATERIAL WHICH WAS APPROX.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: AIRWAYBILL NUMBER: BNA 005761747-154 LAX  ON 10/20/93, SORT LEAD JIM BROKAW CONTACTED ME VIA RADIO AND REPORTED THAT A PACKAGE WAS LEAKING IN BLDG. "C" AT OUR FACILITY AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. IT WAS FURTHER REPORTED THAT THE LEAKING SUBSTANCE HAD AN ODOR OF ALCOHOL. I, SHARON L. LOVE, P/T HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALIST, RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AND UPON ARRIVAL I FOUND 1 FIBREBOARD BOX THAT WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID THAT HAD AN ALCOHOL ODOR.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, I FOUND THE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, ALL LOOSELY PACKED TOGETHER: 2 - DRY CHEMICAL FIRE EXTINGUISHERS 1 - 16 OUNCE AEROSOL CAN OF COOPERS IMPASSE COMPLETE PREMISE FLEA SPRAY  726 - BOOK MATCHES  278 - BOX MATCHES  THE LABEL ON THE FLEA SPRAY STATED WARNING "FLAMMABLE".  THE PLASTIC LID HAD COME OFF THE AEROSOL CAN AS THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE IT IN PLACE, WHICH DURING HANDLING AND THE SHIFTING OF THE PACKAGE DURING THE SORT OPERATION WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE PRESS BUTTON RELEASE VALVE TO BE DEPRESSED AND RELEASE SOME OF ITS CONTENTS, THUS LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ-MAT SORT UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.
THE METAL CAN LIDS CAME LOOSE AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A PLASTIC BAG.  ABSORBANT WAS ADDED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.  THE TOTAL LOSS SENT TO MALLINCKRODT TO DISPOSE OF.
